WEBVTT

00:02.040 --> 00:03.670
Dre: Americans love charity.

00:03.670 --> 00:06.040
The only thing
we love more than charity

00:06.040 --> 00:08.790
is being recognized
for doing charity.

00:08.790 --> 00:13.290
I mean, Angelina Jolie has
a specific charity outfit.

00:13.290 --> 00:16.120
Don't get me wrong --
she brings a lot of joy

00:16.120 --> 00:17.920
to children around the world,

00:17.920 --> 00:20.330
but she also brings
camera crews.

00:20.330 --> 00:23.790
And these days, everyone's
getting in on the action.

00:23.790 --> 00:26.750
Athletes wear their charitable
acts on their sleeves

00:26.750 --> 00:29.120
and cleats and mouth guards

00:29.120 --> 00:32.040
and those little
hand-drying-towel thingies.

00:32.040 --> 00:35.000
And everyone wore
LIVESTRONG bracelets

00:35.000 --> 00:38.500
until Lance Armstrong
turned out to be a cheater.

00:38.500 --> 00:42.040
Every cause imaginable
has a ribbon

00:42.040 --> 00:44.670
that people can wear
to show off their support.

00:44.670 --> 00:46.540
I don't even know
what that one's for.

00:46.540 --> 00:48.080
He might just like ribbons.

00:48.080 --> 00:50.580
But despite America's obsession

00:50.580 --> 00:52.500
with getting attention
for giving back,

00:52.500 --> 00:54.080
that's not me.

00:54.080 --> 00:56.540
I like to keep a low profile.

00:56.540 --> 00:59.080
Okay, maybe not
with all my choices.

00:59.080 --> 01:02.210
But when it comes to charity,
I'm just not that guy.

01:02.210 --> 01:06.210
Congratulations, Dre.
You are our new charity guy.

01:06.210 --> 01:08.210
I don't think
I'm the right person for this.

01:08.210 --> 01:09.460
[ Scoffs ] I'm sorry.

01:09.460 --> 01:11.420
I didn't mean to make it
sound like you had a choice.

01:11.420 --> 01:13.920
♪♪

01:17.790 --> 01:20.710
♪♪

01:20.710 --> 01:22.960
Okay, so why me?

01:22.960 --> 01:25.380
Dre, seeing as you run
our urban division,

01:25.380 --> 01:27.460
and "urban" and "poverty"
mean the same thing,

01:27.460 --> 01:29.040
it feels like
you're the natural choice

01:29.040 --> 01:30.460
to lead our new campaign.

01:30.460 --> 01:32.620
So, is that supposed
to make me feel better?

01:32.620 --> 01:34.710
[ Chuckling ] Dre,
I don't care how you feel.

01:34.710 --> 01:38.330
Now, State Farm
has hired us to work on

01:38.330 --> 01:40.420
their Neighborhood of Good
website.

01:40.420 --> 01:42.670
It helps people give back
to their community.

01:42.670 --> 01:43.920
Well, I'm out.

01:43.920 --> 01:46.420
I already fulfilled my community
service requirements

01:46.420 --> 01:48.330
for freeing
those turtles.

01:48.330 --> 01:50.670
Shame they couldn't
clear the highway in time.

01:50.670 --> 01:53.540
Well, I, for one,
love giving back.

01:53.540 --> 01:54.670
I mean,
how else are people

01:54.670 --> 01:56.080
supposed to know
that you're rich?

01:56.080 --> 01:58.580
Plus, for every one
good public deed you do,

01:58.580 --> 02:00.880
you get to do three evil ones
in private.

02:00.880 --> 02:01.880
That's right.

02:01.880 --> 02:03.670
Connor pulled a puppy dog

02:03.670 --> 02:05.120
out of the L.A. River
last night,

02:05.120 --> 02:06.920
so watch your backs, people.

02:06.920 --> 02:08.210
Someone has a hall pass!

02:08.210 --> 02:09.210
[ Laughs ]

02:09.210 --> 02:11.290
I think giving back
is great.

02:11.290 --> 02:12.880
It gets you into
the sickest galas.

02:12.880 --> 02:15.620
Hey, remember that fete
to end the decimation
of the rainforest?

02:15.620 --> 02:17.290
Oh, boy.

02:17.290 --> 02:19.540
You know what really got
decimated that night?

02:19.540 --> 02:21.710
♪ The dance floor,
the dance floor ♪

02:21.710 --> 02:24.540
[ Imitates techo beat ]
This is what I hate.

02:24.540 --> 02:26.080
It's not about giving back.

02:26.080 --> 02:28.080
It's about the parties
and how it makes you look.

02:28.080 --> 02:30.330
You -- You always make it
about yourselves.

02:30.330 --> 02:32.830
Look, the Leslie Stevens
Aquatic Center

02:32.830 --> 02:36.250
for the Leslie Stevens Swim Team
isn't about Leslie Stevens.

02:36.250 --> 02:37.620
-No?
-No!

02:37.620 --> 02:40.380
It's about those
hardworking kids --

02:40.380 --> 02:43.830
Phelpsy and...Swimmy
and Nemo and...

02:43.830 --> 02:45.620
Obviously,
I don't know their real names,

02:45.620 --> 02:47.080
but that's not the point.

02:47.080 --> 02:48.960
I went to school
with a Swimmy Jenkins.

02:48.960 --> 02:50.210
He drowned.

02:50.210 --> 02:52.330
So wait. You don't give back
at all, Dre?

02:52.330 --> 02:54.210
No,
I write plenty of checks.

02:54.210 --> 02:56.330
I just choose to do it
anonymously.

02:56.330 --> 02:57.750
I do things
anonymously, too.

02:57.750 --> 02:59.040
I just make sure
to have an alibi.

02:59.040 --> 03:00.250
He's -- He's not joking.

03:00.250 --> 03:02.250
Okay,
can we just all agree

03:02.250 --> 03:04.420
that we give
in different ways,

03:04.420 --> 03:07.330
mine being the best,
and let's get back to work?

03:07.330 --> 03:10.540
So, people log on to
NeighborhoodOfGood.com

03:10.540 --> 03:11.920
and type in
their zip code

03:11.920 --> 03:14.040
to find a local cause
they care about.

03:14.040 --> 03:17.330
Oh, look, there's a
retirement home near my house.
Dre: Oh.

03:17.330 --> 03:20.500
My dad can never find out.
Deal?

03:20.500 --> 03:22.830
♪♪

03:22.830 --> 03:24.250
Ruby: Hey, new driver!

03:24.250 --> 03:27.120
All: Congratulations!

03:27.120 --> 03:29.460
I failed to yield!

03:29.460 --> 03:31.830
How do you fail
a driving test?

03:31.830 --> 03:34.580
It's not entirely
his fault.

03:34.580 --> 03:35.580
Okay, son.

03:35.580 --> 03:37.330
Driving 101.

03:37.330 --> 03:39.580
Now, you mess up,
and you kill your father.

03:39.580 --> 03:42.080
And park!

03:42.080 --> 03:44.330
Your other shoulder,
dummy!

03:44.330 --> 03:45.540
[ Tires squeal ]

03:45.540 --> 03:48.000
Oh, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa!

03:48.000 --> 03:50.210
That cone, that was your mama!
Now she's dead!

03:50.210 --> 03:51.290
Aah!

03:51.290 --> 03:53.830
Don't worry.
You will get it next time, okay?

03:53.830 --> 03:54.920
All right, honey.

03:54.920 --> 03:56.540
That's right, baby.

03:58.170 --> 03:59.670
-Hey!
-You don't want to eat that.

03:59.670 --> 04:01.250
Your mama made it,

04:01.250 --> 04:03.670
and you've tasted
enough failure for one day.

04:03.670 --> 04:05.580
Sorry I ruined the party, guys.

04:05.580 --> 04:07.000
Don't be sorry.

04:07.000 --> 04:08.830
It's our fault
for believing in you.

04:08.830 --> 04:09.960
[ Balloon pops ]

04:09.960 --> 04:11.580
You did this.

04:12.790 --> 04:14.080
All right,
that's enough.

04:14.080 --> 04:15.620
Go, go, go, go, go,
go, go, go, go.

04:18.250 --> 04:20.000
I blew it, Grandma.

04:20.000 --> 04:24.380
Every teenager dreams about
driving their siblings around.

04:24.380 --> 04:26.960
With Zoey leaving,
I wanted to step up.

04:26.960 --> 04:28.580
Now there's a power vacuum.

04:28.580 --> 04:30.960
Like when Jermaine
went solo.

04:30.960 --> 04:34.710
Or like before Cersei Lannister
took over at King's Landing.

04:34.710 --> 04:37.420
Ooh, it's hard sometimes
to root for you, baby.

04:37.420 --> 04:39.750
Now, if you really want
the little ones

04:39.750 --> 04:42.290
to respect you
like they respect Zoey,

04:42.290 --> 04:43.710
you got to earn it.

04:43.710 --> 04:45.460
Try doing something cool,

04:45.460 --> 04:48.580
like teach them how to turn
a soda can into a pipe

04:48.580 --> 04:50.620
like my sister taught me!

04:50.620 --> 04:51.920
[ Chuckles ]

04:51.920 --> 04:54.170
Is Grandma's idea
illegal now?

04:54.170 --> 04:56.540
It was never legal?

04:56.540 --> 05:00.580
All I'm saying is do something
nice for the babies.

05:00.580 --> 05:01.710
Okay.

05:01.710 --> 05:03.330
You can die in war,

05:03.330 --> 05:06.170
but you can't
smoke out of a soda can.

05:06.170 --> 05:09.710
So, Stevens put me in charge
of the campaign of giving back.

05:09.710 --> 05:12.210
Uh-huh.
Then they judged me
on how I give back.

05:12.210 --> 05:13.880
I'm a generous man!

05:13.880 --> 05:15.710
Yeah, Dre,
you're generous.

05:15.710 --> 05:19.040
I mean, it's usually
in the form of checks.

05:19.040 --> 05:20.460
You don't really
get involved.

05:20.460 --> 05:21.750
And you do?

05:21.750 --> 05:24.960
I spent two weeks
fixing cleft palates

05:24.960 --> 05:27.250
in Honduras last year.

05:27.250 --> 05:28.540
[ Chuckling ]
That's involved.

05:28.540 --> 05:31.670
Oh, okay, you would think that
I would remember that, do--

05:31.670 --> 05:33.290
Was this during
March Madness?

05:33.290 --> 05:35.120
-Ohh!
-Come on! No!

05:35.120 --> 05:37.120
-[ Laughs ]
-No! Oh, man!

05:37.120 --> 05:38.380
[ Laughs ]

05:38.380 --> 05:40.330
Oh, hey, babe.
How was your day?

05:40.330 --> 05:42.750
My day? Dre, I've been gone
for two weeks.

05:42.750 --> 05:44.380
You were supposed to pick me up
at the airport.

05:44.380 --> 05:47.000
-Was I?
-No, I was.

05:47.000 --> 05:49.380
You were supposed to pick up
the kids after soccer practice.

05:49.380 --> 05:50.500
Ooh.

05:50.500 --> 05:53.080
We had to cross
a freeway!

05:53.080 --> 05:54.920
All I'm saying
is that giving your time

05:54.920 --> 05:56.000
is very meaningful,
Dre.

05:56.000 --> 05:57.380
Like, maybe you can
come with me

05:57.380 --> 06:00.670
when I go down and volunteer
at St. Mark's.

06:00.670 --> 06:03.620
Bow, you know I don't [bleep]
with homeless people.

06:03.620 --> 06:07.040
How can you have beef with
the world's neediest people?

06:07.040 --> 06:10.080
I can't explain it, all right?
They just freak me out.

06:10.080 --> 06:12.750
Kinda like the way you are
with grown people with braces.

06:12.750 --> 06:14.920
You should have done it
when you were 10 years old.

06:14.920 --> 06:16.290
You missed your window.

06:16.290 --> 06:18.080
It's disgusting.
-[ Scoffs ]

06:18.080 --> 06:20.750
Sweetie, just start small,
you know?

06:20.750 --> 06:22.920
Take a bag of clothes
from your closet.

06:22.920 --> 06:25.170
Babe!
I wear all of my clothes.

06:25.170 --> 06:27.500
You have six
green jackets, Dre.

06:28.960 --> 06:30.710
They're not just green.

06:32.960 --> 06:34.330
These two
are exactly the same.

06:34.330 --> 06:36.920
Well, this one
is for a cool morning

06:36.920 --> 06:38.790
that's gonna turn
into a hot day,

06:38.790 --> 06:40.460
and this one
is for a hot day

06:40.460 --> 06:41.880
that's gonna turn
into a cool evening.

06:43.170 --> 06:44.830
-Dre --
-Okay, okay, Bow.

06:44.830 --> 06:46.540
Just one bag, all right?

06:46.540 --> 06:49.420
But my green leather jacket
is off the table.

06:49.420 --> 06:51.330
Babe,
this is green leather.
Yeah.

06:51.330 --> 06:55.000
You just don't find that.
It finds you.

06:55.000 --> 06:56.920
What are you do--
What are you doing?

06:56.920 --> 06:58.210
What are you doing?

06:58.210 --> 06:59.420
I'm wearing it to bed.

06:59.420 --> 07:02.330
Dr--
You're gonna sweat, babe.

07:02.330 --> 07:04.420
As I was hauling my ass
across town

07:04.420 --> 07:07.710
to prove how charitable I was,
it hit me --

07:07.710 --> 07:10.040
if shelters really wanted help,

07:10.040 --> 07:12.750
they would be more
conveniently located.

07:12.750 --> 07:15.710
But then the universe
gave me a gift

07:15.710 --> 07:19.960
in the form of a homeless man
who looked like a 46 regular.

07:19.960 --> 07:23.670
I gave him everything.

07:23.670 --> 07:26.380
♪♪

07:26.380 --> 07:28.790
Except those limited-edition
Huaraches.

07:28.790 --> 07:30.750
I'm not Gandhi.

07:30.750 --> 07:33.460
Listen up, siblingos.

07:33.460 --> 07:37.170
Guess who's taking you
on an adventure tomorrow?

07:37.170 --> 07:38.500
Bah!
[ Car alarm blaring ]

07:38.500 --> 07:40.750
That was
the panic button.

07:40.750 --> 07:43.080
I cannot
seem to turn it off.

07:43.080 --> 07:45.210
But you can't drive us!

07:45.210 --> 07:46.790
You failed the test!

07:46.790 --> 07:49.000
[ Blaring continues ]

07:49.000 --> 07:50.330
Really?

07:50.330 --> 07:51.420
[ Blaring stops ]

07:51.420 --> 07:52.790
But I can drive you

07:52.790 --> 07:56.170
if someone in the car
is over 25.

07:56.170 --> 07:58.170
And not to brag,
but I know someone

07:58.170 --> 08:00.250
who's significantly
over 25.

08:00.250 --> 08:02.330
Significantly?

08:02.330 --> 08:03.790
I don't know who you
talking about, little boy.

08:03.790 --> 08:04.750
Sorry, Grandma.

08:04.750 --> 08:06.580
Mm-hmm. Now, listen.

08:06.580 --> 08:09.000
When we are out in the streets
[chuckles]

08:09.000 --> 08:11.580
do not call me "Grandma."

08:11.580 --> 08:13.540
Okay...

08:13.540 --> 08:14.750
Big Mama J.

08:14.750 --> 08:17.500
Got it, Big Mama J.

08:17.500 --> 08:20.920
Who is ready
to take a trip to...

08:20.920 --> 08:22.790
[ Imitating drumroll ]

08:22.790 --> 08:24.250
Why isn't he using
the table?

08:24.250 --> 08:25.040
I don't know.

08:26.790 --> 08:28.580
...the California
Science Center?!

08:28.580 --> 08:30.460
Yeah!

08:30.460 --> 08:32.040
-Why?
-Hard pass.

08:32.040 --> 08:34.000
No. W-Wait. You haven't
even heard the best part.

08:34.000 --> 08:35.420
We're not going?

08:35.420 --> 08:38.080
No, they have an exhibit
called the Rot Room

08:38.080 --> 08:41.000
where you can watch
a possum rot in real time.

08:41.000 --> 08:44.120
Which part do you think
the maggots eat first?

08:44.120 --> 08:46.670
Spoiler alert --
it's the eyes.

08:46.670 --> 08:49.210
[ Ruby laughs ]
I get it.

08:49.210 --> 08:51.580
The classic
bait and switch.

08:51.580 --> 08:53.960
Say you're doing
something terrible

08:53.960 --> 08:57.500
but actually going
somewhere amazing.

08:57.500 --> 09:00.290
No, we're actually going
to the Science Center.

09:00.290 --> 09:01.830
Okay, fine, baby.

09:01.830 --> 09:04.080
Don't tell us
where we're really going.

09:04.080 --> 09:05.000
Is it SeaWorld?

09:06.420 --> 09:08.040
Thanks for the ride, Dre.

09:08.040 --> 09:09.750
I'm leaving my car
at the office

09:09.750 --> 09:12.330
so Stevens thinks I'm at work
all the time.

09:12.330 --> 09:13.830
But won't he know
you're not there?

09:14.920 --> 09:17.620
Way to go, Charles.
Burning the midnight oil.

09:19.710 --> 09:22.290
That CPR dummy
actually got me a raise.

09:22.290 --> 09:24.120
And it taught me CPR.

09:24.120 --> 09:25.880
[ Indistinct talking
over radio ]

09:25.880 --> 09:35.830
♪♪

09:35.830 --> 09:39.830
♪♪

09:39.830 --> 09:42.040
Dre, do you believe
that a person

09:42.040 --> 09:44.460
can simultaneously be
in two places,

09:44.460 --> 09:46.710
effectively bending
the space-time continuum?

09:46.710 --> 09:48.250
No.

09:48.250 --> 09:50.960
Because you're right here,
but you're also over there.

09:50.960 --> 09:52.790
[ Chuckles ]
Oh, no, man.

09:52.790 --> 09:55.120
That's just a homeless dude
I gave some clothes to.

09:55.120 --> 09:57.500
I'm kind of a hero.
No big deal.

09:57.500 --> 09:59.500
No, no, no.
It is a big deal.

09:59.500 --> 10:00.960
Especially
when you find out

10:00.960 --> 10:02.420
your secret twin
walks the Earth.

10:02.420 --> 10:04.670
Damn, he got that hat
cocked just right.

10:04.670 --> 10:08.460
Outdoor Dre puts together stuff
way better than you do.

10:08.460 --> 10:09.670
Less matchy-matchy.

10:09.670 --> 10:11.830
Ha!
No, man, you're crazy, man.

10:11.830 --> 10:13.290
That dude is nothing
like me.

10:13.290 --> 10:14.670
[ Like Dre ] Ha!

10:14.670 --> 10:17.290
♪♪

10:22.000 --> 10:23.250
Dre: Can you believe that
there's a homeless man out there

10:23.250 --> 10:24.460
that looks like me?
What are you
talking about, Dre?

10:24.460 --> 10:26.080
I'm talking about the man
I gave all my clothes to

10:26.080 --> 10:27.210
on the street
this morning.

10:27.210 --> 10:28.420
You didn't go
to the shelter?

10:28.420 --> 10:29.880
Of course I didn't.

10:29.880 --> 10:31.540
Nobody wants
to go to a shelter.

10:31.540 --> 10:33.620
People in shelters
don't want to go to a shelter.

10:33.620 --> 10:37.000
So, you gave your clothes
to a homeless man

10:37.000 --> 10:39.330
and you're upset
because he's wearing them?

10:39.330 --> 10:40.580
Yes!

10:40.580 --> 10:42.580
Most people feel good

10:42.580 --> 10:44.880
when they help out
the less fortunate.

10:44.880 --> 10:46.420
Think about it, Bow.

10:46.420 --> 10:49.120
If he robs a bank,
I go to jail for 10 years.

10:49.120 --> 10:50.880
If he skips out
on tipping the barista,

10:50.880 --> 10:52.420
somebody's spitting
in my drink!

10:52.420 --> 10:55.460
Yeah, those are two equally
terrible outcomes.

10:55.460 --> 10:56.920
[ Doorbell rings ]
See?!

10:56.920 --> 10:58.960
Hey, Janine.

10:58.960 --> 11:01.330
-Hey, Bow.
-Hey. [ Laughs ]

11:01.330 --> 11:03.170
Oh, I got
to tell you something,

11:03.170 --> 11:04.790
and I don't know
how to say it.

11:04.790 --> 11:06.380
Oh, well, then
let's just skip it.

11:06.380 --> 11:08.380
[ Both laugh ]
You know me...

11:08.380 --> 11:10.000
Yeah.
...and I don't like to get
in other people's business.

11:10.000 --> 11:12.710
I do not
at all know that.

11:12.710 --> 11:14.670
Gal to gal,

11:14.670 --> 11:17.830
there's something...
you should know.

11:17.830 --> 11:21.380
I was getting my post-shrink,
pre-yoga coffee

11:21.380 --> 11:23.880
when I saw Dre
passed out on a bench.

11:23.880 --> 11:26.750
I didn't touch him.

11:26.750 --> 11:30.420
No, it's -- it's not weird.
He's my neighbor.

11:30.420 --> 11:32.830
Janine, that wasn't Dre.

11:32.830 --> 11:35.380
Of course it wasn't.
I know all about denial.

11:35.380 --> 11:36.960
When I caught
Bruce cheating,

11:36.960 --> 11:38.330
I told myself
all kinds of things.

11:38.330 --> 11:40.040
You know,
that it was just a fling,

11:40.040 --> 11:42.210
that his Instagram account
had been hacked.

11:42.210 --> 11:45.670
That it --
That it wasn't my sister.

11:45.670 --> 11:47.210
-Mm.
-You know what?

11:47.210 --> 11:48.790
I'm here for you,

11:48.790 --> 11:52.460
as is the rest
of this community.

11:52.460 --> 11:55.250
What -- I don't --
What have you done, Janine?

11:55.250 --> 11:57.170
I think you're in a lot more
trouble than you believe.

11:57.170 --> 11:59.170
Like, you're in some deep,
deep, like, trouble,

11:59.170 --> 12:00.710
like, deeper than --
-Yep. Okay.

12:00.710 --> 12:03.380
Dre, there is
a homeless man out there

12:03.380 --> 12:05.000
parading through the streets
as you.

12:05.000 --> 12:07.170
Don't just sit there.
Do something!

12:07.170 --> 12:08.500
So now it's on
because the white woman

12:08.500 --> 12:09.710
got you to see it my way,
huh?

12:09.710 --> 12:11.540
Exactly.

12:11.540 --> 12:13.880
Okay, I've got the Purell,
and the Purell you Purell with

12:13.880 --> 12:15.960
once you close the cap
on the first Purell.

12:15.960 --> 12:17.580
Let's get this show
on the road.

12:17.580 --> 12:19.920
Zoey usually lets us listen
to the hip-hop station

12:19.920 --> 12:21.710
that doesn't bleep out
the bad words.

12:21.710 --> 12:23.460
Well,
I'll do you one better.

12:23.460 --> 12:26.120
I've got a podcast
about South Asian geopolitics

12:26.120 --> 12:28.580
that will blow
your hair back.

12:28.580 --> 12:31.460
Hey,
you're losing them fast.

12:31.460 --> 12:33.460
♪♪

12:33.460 --> 12:36.170
I had to do something
about my homeless twin,

12:36.170 --> 12:38.790
so I went to someone
who knows how to think

12:38.790 --> 12:40.540
outside the box.

12:40.540 --> 12:42.620
-What the hell?
-Sorry, Dre.

12:42.620 --> 12:45.460
I had to set up Chauncey because
I had to go to the bathroom.

12:45.460 --> 12:47.290
And then check out a movie.
What's up?

12:47.290 --> 12:49.420
Man, this homeless dude
is in my head.

12:49.420 --> 12:50.710
I need to do
something about him.

12:50.710 --> 12:52.040
Take him out.

12:52.040 --> 12:53.500
What?
Got it.

12:53.500 --> 12:56.000
I'm honored that
you would come to me, Dre.

12:56.000 --> 12:58.670
But know this --
a time will come

12:58.670 --> 13:00.500
where I will demand
the same from you as well.

13:00.500 --> 13:01.790
What? No.

13:01.790 --> 13:03.330
No, Charlie,
I know this sounds bad, man.

13:03.330 --> 13:05.580
I just need people
to stop thinking he's me.

13:05.580 --> 13:06.670
I'm not homeless.

13:06.670 --> 13:08.290
Oh.

13:08.290 --> 13:09.830
Maybe I should
change up my look.

13:09.830 --> 13:12.830
No. You can't change up
your matchy-matchy look, Dre.

13:12.830 --> 13:14.540
That's your look.

13:14.540 --> 13:18.120
Here you are in
dope bleached denim. Hmm?

13:18.120 --> 13:21.080
What about that wine-colored,
fur-collared bomber jacket, huh?

13:21.080 --> 13:22.290
-Yeah.
-And here you are,

13:22.290 --> 13:25.250
rocking head-to-toe
Givenchy.

13:25.250 --> 13:27.080
And people said
it couldn't be done.

13:27.080 --> 13:28.250
[ Scoffs ]
But I did it.

13:28.250 --> 13:29.790
You did that.

13:29.790 --> 13:31.580
I forgot
I posted these pics.

13:31.580 --> 13:35.170
Uh, uh, you didn't.
It was on your wife's feed.

13:35.170 --> 13:37.580
And why did she stop posting
early-morning selfies?

13:37.580 --> 13:39.250
-What?
-Nothing.

13:39.250 --> 13:40.710
Get him some new clothes.

13:40.710 --> 13:42.540
Swap them out
for your old ones.

13:42.540 --> 13:44.120
That's not a bad idea.

13:44.120 --> 13:46.920
And neither
is early-morning selfies.

13:46.920 --> 13:49.790
Just mention it.

13:49.790 --> 13:53.170
Woman: In the 17th century,
the Hmong people of Cambodia

13:53.170 --> 13:55.380
mostly stayed in the mountains

13:55.380 --> 13:58.170
to fend off the incursions
of the Hen Warriors.

13:58.170 --> 13:59.670
Primarily...

13:59.670 --> 14:01.710
[ Cellphone rings ]

14:01.710 --> 14:03.380
Who dis?
Man: Hey, Ruby.

14:03.380 --> 14:04.420
What are you wearing?

14:04.420 --> 14:06.120
I'm over here
butt-ass naked.

14:06.120 --> 14:07.670
Excuse me, sir.

14:07.670 --> 14:09.380
This is a PG car.
[ Laughter ]

14:09.380 --> 14:11.290
No, no, no.
I-It's a wrong number.

14:11.290 --> 14:12.920
Wrong number!

14:12.920 --> 14:14.460
I'll call you back,
Francis.

14:16.120 --> 14:18.080
Diane: What are you doing?
Where are we going?

14:18.080 --> 14:19.830
We're low
on wiper fluid.

14:19.830 --> 14:21.250
Forgot to check
before we left.

14:21.250 --> 14:24.040
I am sorry
I put you all at risk.

14:27.420 --> 14:29.500
[ Thud ]

14:29.500 --> 14:30.500
Uh-oh.

14:30.500 --> 14:31.620
It's fine.

14:31.620 --> 14:33.460
You barely
scratched the paint.

14:33.460 --> 14:35.080
I better leave a note.

14:35.080 --> 14:36.460
What are you talking about?

14:36.460 --> 14:38.290
I've seen Dad take off
a side mirror

14:38.290 --> 14:40.170
with a shopping cart
and not even blink.

14:40.170 --> 14:42.750
Hurry up so we can go to
the place I don't want to go to.

14:42.750 --> 14:49.580
♪♪

14:49.580 --> 14:53.170
Um. Well, uh
[chuckles nervously]

14:53.170 --> 14:54.790
guess we have to wait for him
to get back

14:54.790 --> 14:57.170
so I can explain it to him
in person.

14:57.170 --> 14:59.040
Don't worry.
I've got a podcast

14:59.040 --> 15:01.750
about the Armenian genocide,
so...

15:01.750 --> 15:03.580
What is wrong
with this dude?

15:03.580 --> 15:07.620
Dre: So was I stealing my stuff
back from a homeless man?

15:07.620 --> 15:10.620
Yes.
But I was doing him a favor.

15:10.620 --> 15:14.330
My dope Gucci threads made him
a target on the streets.

15:14.330 --> 15:17.920
He's actually safer with cheap
sweats from a big-box store.

15:17.920 --> 15:20.000
But as I looked at his stuff,

15:20.000 --> 15:23.670
I realized this wasn't
just a homeless version of me.

15:23.670 --> 15:27.750
This was a real person,
a man who has a life.

15:29.080 --> 15:31.170
I'm moving, I'm moving,
I'm moving.

15:31.170 --> 15:33.580
Hey, no, no, no, no.
It's cool, man.

15:33.580 --> 15:34.710
It's cool.

15:34.710 --> 15:37.120
Hey, uh...

15:37.120 --> 15:38.830
let me buy you
a cup of coffee.

15:38.830 --> 15:40.670
You're not gonna talk to me
about God, are you?

15:40.670 --> 15:42.250
No, we straight, man.

15:42.250 --> 15:43.960
We cool. Just coffee.

15:50.000 --> 15:51.920
Look at this.
Whole bag of orange, 2 bucks!

15:51.920 --> 15:56.170
Look at this --
a concert t-shirt for 5 bucks.

15:56.170 --> 15:59.170
There's no "K" in Tyrese.
Is there?

15:59.170 --> 16:03.000
Junior?! How did you not
notice this earlier?!

16:03.000 --> 16:05.290
-What?
-It's bright orange!

16:05.290 --> 16:08.330
I-I saw it. I just thought
it was a super cool hubcap.

16:08.330 --> 16:10.170
We've been waiting around
forever

16:10.170 --> 16:12.580
for someone whose dead body
is probably in that trunk.

16:12.580 --> 16:15.790
You know what? Forget it.
Let's just go home.

16:15.790 --> 16:17.540
Well, what about
the Science Center?

16:17.540 --> 16:20.420
What's the point?
It closes in half an hour.

16:20.420 --> 16:23.380
Oh! SeaWorld's
open till 9:00.

16:23.380 --> 16:25.080
We were never
going to SeaWorld.

16:25.080 --> 16:26.960
I wasn't sure
what I was going to say,

16:26.960 --> 16:28.620
but it turned out Greg and I

16:28.620 --> 16:30.670
had more in common
than we realized.

16:30.670 --> 16:33.290
But the Fox Hill Mall
was the spot!
Yeah, man.

16:33.290 --> 16:35.290
I got caught shoplifting
at the Penney's there.

16:35.290 --> 16:36.210
Me too!

16:36.210 --> 16:38.380
Both: Ha!

16:38.380 --> 16:40.540
Yo, thanks
for the clothes, man.

16:40.540 --> 16:42.170
People are always trying
to give me some stained shirts

16:42.170 --> 16:44.040
or some old,
off-brand sweats.

16:44.040 --> 16:45.500
Oh, well, you know,
at least you're getting

16:45.500 --> 16:47.040
some new off-brand sweats.

16:47.040 --> 16:48.120
Those are nice.

16:48.120 --> 16:50.080
They okay.

16:50.080 --> 16:51.960
But the stuff
you hooked me up with, man,

16:51.960 --> 16:53.920
made me feel good
about myself.

16:53.920 --> 16:55.500
I'm glad
it made a difference.

16:55.500 --> 16:57.000
It did, man.

16:57.000 --> 16:59.710
Hey, it's not every day
you get a Tom Ford blazer.

16:59.710 --> 17:02.920
[ Laughs ] I --
I gave you my Tom Ford?

17:02.920 --> 17:05.710
[ Chuckles ] That was in the bag
to go to the cleaners,

17:05.710 --> 17:08.210
but, uh...enjoy.

17:09.380 --> 17:10.420
Ha!

17:10.420 --> 17:12.540
Ha...

17:14.250 --> 17:17.290
Hey.
How was the Science Center?

17:17.290 --> 17:18.790
We didn't even
get there.
What?

17:18.790 --> 17:20.830
We spent all our time
at a gas station.

17:20.830 --> 17:24.670
I wanted to deliver a fun
and informative outing,

17:24.670 --> 17:27.250
but instead they got
street oranges.

17:27.250 --> 17:28.540
It was a total waste
of a day.

17:28.540 --> 17:29.750
Mm.

17:29.750 --> 17:32.120
Well, not a total waste.

17:32.120 --> 17:33.880
Today, I learned more
from that gas station

17:33.880 --> 17:34.960
than I learned
from Mom ever.

17:34.960 --> 17:36.500
Hey!

17:36.500 --> 17:38.790
Yeah, she never lets us
get out and wander.

17:38.790 --> 17:40.920
'Cause that's how
kids get snatched!

17:40.920 --> 17:43.080
But there was so much
cool stuff in there.

17:43.080 --> 17:45.040
This thing is shaped
like a tree

17:45.040 --> 17:46.790
and it smells
like a tree.

17:46.790 --> 17:48.330
Plus, I got a t-shirt

17:48.330 --> 17:49.880
and these Boost Mobile
burner phones.

17:49.880 --> 17:51.080
Burner phones?

17:51.080 --> 17:53.080
Shh! We need those
for a thing.

17:53.080 --> 17:54.330
Oh, good call.
Good call.

17:54.330 --> 17:55.830
Ruby: I'll talk to you later,
Francis.

17:55.830 --> 17:57.290
And put on some clothes.

17:57.290 --> 17:58.330
-Oh, Grandma!
-Huh?

17:58.330 --> 17:59.880
Will you chaperone
again tomorrow?

17:59.880 --> 18:02.120
We want Junior to take us
on the freeway.

18:02.120 --> 18:03.710
Come on.
Say you'll drive us.

18:03.710 --> 18:05.580
We have side bets going
to see if you'll cry, so...

18:05.580 --> 18:07.170
Mm...

18:07.170 --> 18:08.710
I'm down.
-Yes!

18:08.710 --> 18:11.620
But that's a sucker's bet.
I'm definitely gonna cry.

18:11.620 --> 18:13.880
[ Laughter ]

18:13.880 --> 18:16.420
I didn't tell Bow
about my shameless plan

18:16.420 --> 18:18.500
to steal
a homeless man's clothes,

18:18.500 --> 18:20.960
but I did tell her
about my time with Greg.

18:20.960 --> 18:24.420
It was weird, babe.
We have a lot in common.

18:24.420 --> 18:27.790
We both hate the Lakers,
we both are fans of Tom Ford,

18:27.790 --> 18:30.920
and we both got our ears pierced
at the Fox Hills Mall.

18:30.920 --> 18:34.080
See?
Doesn't giving back feel good?

18:34.080 --> 18:35.750
Here's the thing,
though.
Hmm.

18:35.750 --> 18:36.790
It didn't.

18:36.790 --> 18:39.880
-What?
-It felt scary.

18:39.880 --> 18:42.210
He's just like me.

18:42.210 --> 18:44.880
Babe, a-a-and spending time
with him made me realize

18:44.880 --> 18:48.210
that my life could've gone
very differently.

18:48.210 --> 18:49.670
Sweetie,
you can't think like that.

18:49.670 --> 18:51.580
It's hard not to.

18:51.580 --> 18:53.880
You know,
when I was growing up,

18:53.880 --> 18:56.460
it felt like we were always
just one paycheck away

18:56.460 --> 18:57.670
from being homeless
ourselves.

18:57.670 --> 18:59.040
Mm.

18:59.040 --> 19:01.420
One slipup,
one missed day of work

19:01.420 --> 19:03.000
and we would have been
in that shelter.

19:03.000 --> 19:04.670
Mm.

19:04.670 --> 19:06.460
I guess that's why I don't
[bleep] with the homeless.

19:06.460 --> 19:08.920
Okay,
there has got to be

19:08.920 --> 19:10.790
a better way
for you to say that.
It --

19:10.790 --> 19:12.250
And I know it's awkward,

19:12.250 --> 19:15.420
but maybe
because you do relate,

19:15.420 --> 19:17.290
you could make more
of a difference.

19:17.290 --> 19:19.170
-You're right.
-Mm-hmm.

19:19.170 --> 19:20.710
And it did feel good
not to be anonymous.

19:20.710 --> 19:23.880
Right? Listen.

19:23.880 --> 19:26.540
When I went
to Tegucigalpa...
Mm-hmm.

19:26.540 --> 19:29.290
...and I saw the faces
of those needy children --

19:29.290 --> 19:31.460
Babe,
we're still talking about me.

19:31.460 --> 19:32.580
Oh, wow.
[ Doorbell rings ]

19:32.580 --> 19:33.880
-Hel--
-[ Stammers ]

19:33.880 --> 19:35.710
[ Whispers ]
Don't -- Don't say anything.

19:35.710 --> 19:36.830
-What?
-Shh.

19:36.830 --> 19:39.330
Janine: Bow, Dre?
I-I know you're in there.

19:39.330 --> 19:41.880
I made you some lasagna,
seeing as how you guys...

19:41.880 --> 19:44.330
Oh, my God, this woman.
...are in a super bad place
right now.

19:44.330 --> 19:46.210
I don't.
It's still real hot.

19:46.210 --> 19:48.290
Baby, I don't eat red meat.
It's p-piping hot, actually.

19:48.290 --> 19:49.790
I'm just gonna set it here
on your...
[ Both stammering ]

19:49.790 --> 19:51.830
...your welcome -- Ah! Oh, boy.
[ Clatter ]

19:51.830 --> 19:53.120
Okay, I dropped it.

19:53.120 --> 19:55.000
Okay.
Top layer's
a little wonky now.

19:55.000 --> 19:56.920
She dropped it.
Oh, there's
marinara everywhere.

19:56.920 --> 19:57.920
It's like a murder scene.

19:57.920 --> 19:59.290
Just leave it!

20:04.880 --> 20:08.170
Ugh, the trash is full.

20:08.170 --> 20:11.540
Who is throwing away
a perfectly good Tykrese shirt?

20:11.540 --> 20:21.540
♪♪

20:21.540 --> 20:22.790
♪♪

20:22.790 --> 20:24.710
Hey! Hey, hey, hey.
Get out of there.

20:24.710 --> 20:26.670
H-Hey, Janine.
It's okay. It's me.

20:26.670 --> 20:28.080
Oh, hey, Dre.

20:28.080 --> 20:31.040
Oh, man. Bow said you'd fallen
on hard times.

20:31.040 --> 20:32.540
What was it?
Gambling? Drugs?

20:32.540 --> 20:34.580
Prostitution?
An unholy trifecta?

20:34.580 --> 20:36.670
Thank you, Janine,
but we're doing just fine.

20:36.670 --> 20:39.170
Okay, I know. You don't want
charity, so I'm just gonna leave

20:39.170 --> 20:43.170
an untouched KFC family bucket
in the trash around 5:30.

20:43.170 --> 20:44.620
You guys like wings,
right?

20:44.620 --> 20:46.040
-No, Janine, we're --
-You know what?

20:46.040 --> 20:47.210
Beggars can't be choosers.
[ Laughs ]

20:47.210 --> 20:48.460
God bless.

20:48.460 --> 20:50.040
The kids will eat anything
if they're hungry enough.

20:50.040 --> 20:51.670
You know what I mean?

20:51.670 --> 20:55.620
♪♪
